SPE_description: Base round, often moderately adhesive, with many short, inward directed notches. Colour of column variable, plain with smooth surface.

Base round, adhesive, with no or indistinctive lobes. Column is smooth and transparent with, often light, orange-red colouration. Distinctive light vertical striping pattern characterised by a sequence two close by stripes with a larger intermediate distance between the neighbouring pairs.
Base more or less round, adhesive, with irregular lobes covering the substrate around the base. Juvenile specimens can be plain white or orange but the column is often les transparent than D. cincta.
Freshwater sponge white/yellowish
Tube dextral, rounded in cross section, up to 2 mm in coil diameter. Up to four longitudinal ridges, three easily seen from above in larger specimens, smaller tubes only have one ridge.

Slender and smooth tube, usually not longer than 5 cm (on SETL-plates with three month deployment intervals). Colour of tube greyish brown, colour of chaetae light red to pail orange with darker bands. Spiral arrangement of abdominal chaetae.

Colony thick and encrusting with brownish colouration. 
Zooids, compact, round in shape, arranged hexagonally in regular radiating series, with circular- almost D-shaped orifice. Colony, brown/red.

Colony transparent with no or light brown colouration, thick, encrusting with concrete and smooth edges when intact. Zooids, porous, elongated, twice as long than wide, arranged hexagonally. Orifice located in distal part of zooid, D-shaped curved distally.
Colony encrusting, transparent, zooids small containing red/brown dots.

Colony non-encrusting, bush-shaped, dichotomous branched. Bifurcations starting at the base of the bush-shaped colony. Six-ten zooids between bifurcations. Zooids alternating forming branches of maximum two zooids wide. Zooids transparent containing brown dots.
Fresh water bryozoan, colony non-encrusting, branched, thick brown branches splitting of in light-brown zooids.
Colony non-encrusting feathery. Branches disposed in spirals. Zooids biserially arranged. A single spine on the outer distal part of zooid.
Small orange, solitary globules, one to few mm in diameter
